{{nihongo|'''''Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games'''''|<U+30DE><U+30EA><U+30AA>&<U+30BD><U+30CB><U+30C3><U+30AF> AT <U+30D0><U+30F3><U+30AF><U+30FC><U+30D0><U+30FC><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30F3><U+30D4><U+30C3><U+30AF>|Mario to Sonikku atto Bank<U+016B>b<U+0101> Orinpikku|lit. "Mario & Sonic at the Vancouver Olympics"}}<ref name="Japanese press release">{{cite press release|title={{nihongo|G<U+0113>mu sofuto "Mario to Sonikku atto Bank<U+016B>b<U+0101> Orimpikku" hatsubai kettei! "Mario to Sonikku" atto Pekin Orimpikku" wo zensekai de daihitto saseta yume no kombi ga, arata na orimpikku g<U+0113>mu de kaette kuru!|<U+30B2><U+30FC><U+30E0><U+30BD><U+30D5><U+30C8><U+300E><U+30DE><U+30EA><U+30AA><U+FF06><U+30BD><U+30CB><U+30C3><U+30AF> AT <U+30D0><U+30F3><U+30AF><U+30FC><U+30D0><U+30FC><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30F3><U+30D4><U+30C3><U+30AF><U+300F><U+767A><U+58F2><U+6C7A><U+5B9A><U+FF01><U+300E><U+30DE><U+30EA><U+30AA><U+FF06><U+30BD><U+30CB><U+30C3><U+30AF> AT <U+5317><U+4EAC><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30F3><U+30D4><U+30C3><U+30AF><U+300F><U+3092><U+5168><U+4E16><U+754C><U+3067><U+5927><U+30D2><U+30C3><U+30C8><U+3055><U+305B><U+305F><U+5922><U+306E><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+30D3><U+304C><U+3001><U+65B0><U+305F><U+306A><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30F3><U+30D4><U+30C3><U+30AF><U+30B2><U+30FC><U+30E0><U+3067><U+5E30><U+3063><U+3066><U+304F><U+308B><U+FF01>}}|publisher=Sega|date=2009-02-13|url= http://sega.jp/corp/release/2009/0213/home.shtml|accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref> is a 2009 [[sports game|sports]] [[video game]] developed by [[Sega]]. It was published by [[Nintendo]] for Japan and by Sega for North America and Europe. The game is officially licensed by the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) through exclusive license International Sports Multimedia. The game is the third official crossover title to feature characters from both [[Mario]] and [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]]'s respective universes, the first and second being the game's predecessor [[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]] and [[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]] respectively. It was released on the [[Wii]] and the [[Nintendo DS]] handheld in October 2009, and is the first official video game of the [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Winter Olympic Games]].<ref name="press release">{{cite press release|title=Mario and Sonic Head to the Slopes in Mario and Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games|publisher=Sega|date= 2009-02-12|url=http://www.sega.com/news/?n=3012|accessdate=2009-02-12}}</ref>  

''Mario & Sonic'' on the Wii and DS is a collection of events based on the Olympic Winter Games. Players can assume the role of a Mario or Sonic character while competing against the others in these events. The game features all of the playable characters that were present in its predecessor, as well as four new characters.<ref name="press release"/><ref name=IGNon/>

A third installment, named ''[[Mario & Sonic at the London 2012 Olympic Games]]'', was released for the Wii on November 13, 2011 in Europe, and it was developed for the [[Nintendo 3DS]]. The 3DS counterpart was released in February 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fletcher|first=JC|title=Mario and Sonic at the London 2012 Olympic Games headed to Wii and 3DS|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/04/21/mario-and-sonic-at-the-london-2012-olympic-games-headed-to-wii-a/|accessdate=23 April 2011|newspaper=Joystiq|date=21 April 2011}}</ref> 

==Gameplay==
''Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games'' retains the gameplay mechanics of [[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games|its predecessor]], controlling an on-screen character through authentic Olympic events with the specific tailored controls for the Wii and DS. Unlike its predecessor, some of the events in the Wii game can use the [[Wii Balance Board|Balance Board]] accessory, but it is not a requirement.<ref name=IGNon/>

All of the playable characters from the previous game return in addition to four new characters.<ref name=IGNon>{{cite web| url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/969/969383p1.html|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games Hands-on|accessdate= 2009-04-03|last=Hatfield|first=Daemon|date=2009-04-03|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Fox Interactive Media]]|location=California|pages= 1<U+2013>2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=E3 2009|url=http://www.sega.com|work=[[Sega]]|publisher=Sega Press|date=2009-06-02|accessdate= 2009-06-02}}</ref> It has been announced via the Nintendo Channel, that this game will have WiiConnect24 capability and the player can use their Miis in-game. A new feature added to the player's Mii is the ability to customize the Mii's clothes.<ref>http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/article.php?id=10838</ref>
The sequel introduces a Festival mode in the Wii version that lets players make their way through the entire [[Olympic Games]], from [[Olympic Games ceremony|opening ceremony to closure]].<ref name=IGNon/> The multiplayer mode offers "co-op and competitive gameplay" whereas the DS version will use its wireless capabilities.<ref name="press release"/> The DS counterpart has "Adventure Tours" where players can accept quests and challenge [[Boss (video games)|bosses]] and to stop [[Dr. Eggman]] and [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] before they can stop the Olympics by kidnapping the Snow Spirits. [[Nintendo DS|DS Download Play]] is possible for those without an individual copy of the game.<ref name=IGNon/>

==Development==
<!-- {{see also|Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games#Development|l1=Development of Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games}}-->
In January 2009, a rumor from Spanish Nintendo magazine ''Nintendo Acci<U+00F3>n'' mentioned a sequel to ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]'' would be created for the [[2010 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey|first=Kat|url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3172411|title=Mario & Sonic At The Olympic Games Sequel May Be On The Way|accessdate=2009-02-12|date=2009-01-22| publisher=[[1UP.com]]}}</ref> Both [[IGN]] and [[Eurogamer]] received confirmation on the games' existence, with IGN stating the game will be announced within the following month.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/mario-and-sonic-olympics-2-on-the-way|title=Mario & Sonic Olympics 2 on the way|accessdate= 2009-02-12|last=Gibson|first=Ellie|date=2009-01-22|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/947/947571p1.html|title=Rumor: Mario & Sonic at the Winter Olympics|accessdate=2009-02-12|last=Casamassina|first=Matt|authorlink=Matt Casamassina|date=2009-01-22|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Fox Interactive Media]]|location=California}}</ref> Dennis Kim, licensing and merchandising director for the event, stated in February that a ''Mario & Sonic'' title "[is] being discussed and planned for Vancouver". Kim also stated "Vancouver 2010" and the IOC will share royalties from this game.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Inwood|first1=Damian|title=Mario and Sonic will be part of video-game deal for 2010 Games|newspaper=[[The Province]]|date=2009-02-08|url=http://www2.canada.com/theprovince/news/story.html?id=2c530690-6a11-4c92-bcb3-712d0e449257|format=}}</ref> In the same month, the sequel titled "Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games" was officially announced via a joint press release by Sega and Nintendo on February 12, 2009. So, The game is being developed by Sega Japan under the supervision of Shigeru Miyamoto.<ref name="press release"/> This title is the third video game collaboration between Nintendo and Sega.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://wii.ign.com/articles/776/776878p1.html|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games Interview|accessdate=2007-03-29|last= Burman|first=Rob|date=2007-03-29|publisher=IGN}}</ref> According to gaming site [[IGN]], development began immediately after the initial Olympic game was released in November 2007<!-- and unlike the previous installment the two versions are being developed separately -->.<ref name=IGNon/>

An [[iPhone OS]] app version was released in January 2010 by Sega. Due to only containing Sonic characters, the game is simply titled ''[[Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games]]''.<ref>http://www.appstorehq.com/sonicattheolympicwintergames-iphone-132266/app</ref>

==Reception==
{{VG Reviews
|GR = 77.95% <small>(DS)</small><br/>70.86% <small>(Wii)</small>
|IGN = 6.5/10 <small>(Wii)</small><br/>7.5/10 <small>(DS)</small>
|XPlay = 3.5/5
|GT = 7.2/10
}}
The Wii version of ''Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games'' received a generally positive reaction from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/wii/marioandsonicattheolympicwintergames|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games (wii) reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> The DS version had a higher score than the Wii version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ds/sports/marioandsonicattheolympicwintergames/review.html?mode=web&tag=scoresummary;critic-score|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> <!-- The consensus from the talk page is not the case. It's the scores, which I'm saying nicely, and here there are sources (apparently). Please don't remove the [[good faith]] sources (please). --> GameRankings lists the average scores as 70.86% for the Wii version and 77.95% for the DS.<ref>http://www.gamerankings.com/wii/958083-mario-and-sonic-at-the-olympic-winter-games/index.html</ref><ref>http://www.gamerankings.com/ds/958082-mario-and-sonic-at-the-olympic-winter-games/index.html</ref> IGN said of the Wii version that "Most of the events also use a whole lot of waggle or over-exaggerated remote tilt where controls could have made for a better experience", giving the Wii game a 6.5.<ref>http://wii.ign.com/articles/103/1035150p1.html</ref> [[X-Play]]'s [[Adam Sessler]] noted that the Wii version of the game is too simple and the events are not so great, despite praising the dream events, and saying the controls are too easy. As a result, they gave it a 3 out of 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games Review Videos - G4tv.com|url=http://www.g4tv.com/videos/42200/Mario--Sonic-at-the-Olympic-Winter-Games-Review/|publisher=[[G4 (TV channel)|G4tv.com]]}}</ref> [[GameSpot]] agreed, criticizing the uninteresting mission objectives in the DS version.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games Review for DS - GameSpot|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ds/sports/marioandsonicattheolympicwintergames/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=gssummary&tag=summary;read-review|work=[[GameSpot]]| publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' was very disappointed that players can still use Wi-Fi only for worldwide rankings. No online play is available.<ref>''Nintendo Power'' Vol. 247, November 2009</ref> [[GameTrailers]] also gave the Wii game a 5.2, criticizing the hit and miss motion controls.<ref>http://www.gametrailers.com/video/review-mario/57874</ref> [[GamePro]] agreed, stating that "Where the original had a sense of novelty and charm, the sequel feels a little dated and tired."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/212683/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-winter-games/|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games Review from GamePro|work=[[GamePro]]|publisher=[[IDG]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100222235828/http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/212683/mario-sonic-at-the-olympic-winter-games/|archivedate=2010-02-22}}</ref>

''[[GamesMaster (magazine)|GamesMaster]]'' praised the game, saying that it "justifies the hype."<ref>GamesMaster Dec. 2009</ref> ''[[EuroGamer]]'' also praised the game, stating that "It's true to say that Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games is no Mario Kart. But it's a fun, polished party game with broad appeal, and a marked improvement over the previous one."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/mario-and-sonic-at-the-olympic-winter-games-wii-review|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games Review|publisher=''[[EuroGamer]]''}}</ref> Gamervision praised the game also, stating that "Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games isn<U+2019>t going to surprise anyone with its gameplay, graphics, controls, or concept, but it<U+2019>s a perfectly serviceable party game for the Wii."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamervision.com/gamer/veggie_jackson/reviews/article/mario_amp_sonic_at_the_olympic_winter_games|title=Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games Review|publisher=Gamervision}}</ref> Nintendo Life praised the events of the game, giving it a 9/10.<ref>http://wii.nintendolife.com/reviews/2009/10/mario_and_sonic_at_the_olympic_winter_games_wii</ref> IGN called the DS version "impressive", giving it a 7.5.<ref>http://ds.ign.com/articles/103/1035772p1.html</ref>

By December 31, 2009, the game had sold approximately 5.67 million copies, making it Sega's best-selling game in the fiscal year starting that March.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sega Posts Decline In Nine Month Game Sales|url=http://edge-online.com/news/sega-posts-decline-in-nine-month-game-sales|publisher=''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]''|last=Ivan|first=Tom|date=February 5, 2010|accessdate=April 20, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5q9EO6YBt|archivedate=2010-05-31}}</ref>

